subSubSection.paragraph:
Gravid females were collected in 

July 2008

and eggs were examined via SEM. 
Although
eggs from the 
Alabama
series (
Fig. 19
) were noticeably less pitted and smoother than from 
paratype
females from 
Indiana and Illinois
(
Figs. 21, 23
), both the overall egg shape (i.e., oval; 
Figs. 18, 20, 22
) and collar (i.e., low, gently-rounded open pit; 
Figs. 19, 21, 23
) were too similar to warrant a new species description

.
